THE RISK (context, do not rewrite): perturbation [{"nodeId":"cust.operator-large","op":"set","value":0.28,"note":"Portion of large-operator PDU spend relocates into integrator BOMs foreclosed to a new entrant — absolute shrink of the directly-winnable pool, below the ledger's 0.33 band floor"}], likelihood 0.4, category competitive

FIELDS TO REWRITE:
{
 "title": "The chosen first buyer — large operators — is migrating PDU procurement into ODM whole-rack deals, moving the decision to a channel the venture doesn't sell through",
 "narrative": "The venture's stated Year-1 route is selling to large operators, and cust.operator-large carries the biggest buyer weight (0.40) — justified in the ledger by hyperscale+colo being ~68% of capacity and large operators 'buying direct'. But direct purchase of discrete PDUs is exactly what large operators are unwinding: AI-density capacity is procured as integrated racks from ODM/rack integrators, where power distribution (shelf or PDU) is a BOM line the integrator sources under multi-year white-label agreements with incumbents. The demand doesn't shrink on paper — it relocates from cust.operator-large (where the venture has a channel plan) into cust.oem (where it has none), and BOM slots there are locked by Schneider/Vertiv/Eaton-class relationships years ahead. For a pre-launch entrant, a slice that moves to a foreclosed channel is functionally not addressable, whatever the buyer-mix pie chart says.",
 "mechanism": [
  {
   "step": "trigger",
   "text": "The venture's primary Year-1 buyer is large operators, whose capacity base (hyperscale 48% + colo 20% of worldwide capacity per Synergy end-2025) underpins the 0.40 weight — and whose new AI-density capacity is procured as ODM-integrated racks rather than component PDUs",
   "refs": [
    "profile:Who is the primary buyer you'll sell through first?",
    "digest:seg-mix#c0",
    "digest:seg-mix#c1",
    "ledger:cust.operator-large"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "propagation",
   "text": "When rack power becomes an integrator BOM line, vendor selection shifts to white-label/OEM agreements dominated by the named incumbent set (Schneider at 15.8% plus a 5–7-vendor co-equal leader group per multiple reports); a pre-launch entrant with no ODM qualification cannot contest these slots inside 12 months",
   "refs": [
    "digest:cr3-vendors#c0",
    "digest:cr3-vendors#c6",
    "digest:cr3-vendors#c7",
    "ledger:cust.oem"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "model-impact",
   "text": "cust.operator-large's 0.40 is a needs-source internal estimate resting on one misused company-level order stat with zero published channel data; if a material fraction of large-operator PDU spend flows through integrator channels, the direct-sale pool the venture's entire Year-1 motion targets is overstated — YAM's obtainable assumption is applied to a pool that partly is not there",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:cust.operator-large",
    "ledger:cust.oem",
    "ledger:obtainableFactor"
   ]
  }
 ],
 "whyMissable": "The buyer-mix nodes are flagged 'needs-source', so the team's instinct is to validate the percentages via interviews — checking whether 0.40 is the right number. The risk isn't the number; it's that the category boundary between 'operator buys direct' and 'operator buys a rack' is moving during the entry window, so even a correctly-measured 2025 split is wrong by the time the pipeline matures.",
 "falsifier": "Procurement documentation from 2–3 large CE operators showing intelligent rack PDUs still tendered as a discrete direct-purchase category (separate RFQ line, operator-selected vendor) for their 2026–27 capacity additions, including AI-density halls.",
 "likelihoodRationale": "Integrated-rack procurement is documented for hyperscale AI deployments and the buyer-mix nodes have no evidential floor to resist the shift; however, European colo operators still run discrete PDU RFQs for standard halls, and the pace of channel migration within a 12-month window is genuinely uncertain. [evidence revision: Strong corroboration of the ODM-integrated-rack procurement mechanism and incumbent lock-in of power BOM slots raises confidence in the relocation thesis. However, the falsifying evidence shows PDUs still appear as procured line items (even if bundled into rack infrastructure) and that discrete power-distribution bids to operators persist in Europe, so the channel migration is real but not total within 12 months. Net modest upward revision from 0.35 to 0.40.]"
}

